        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Synchronous server sockets suspend the execution of the application until a connection request is received on the socket.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Synchronous server sockets are not suitable for applications that make heavy use of the network in their operation, but they can be suitable for simple network applications.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>After a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Net.Sockets.Socket&gt;</ph> is set to listen on an endpoint using the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Net.Sockets.Socket.Bind%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Net.Sockets.Socket.Listen%2A&gt;</ph> methods, it is ready to accept incoming connection requests using the <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Net.Sockets.Socket.Accept%2A&gt;</ph> method.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The application is suspended until a connection request is received when the <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Accept<ept id="p1">**</ept> method is called.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>When a connection request is received, <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Accept<ept id="p1">**</ept> returns a new <bpt id="p2">**</bpt>Socket<ept id="p2">**</ept> instance that is associated with the connecting client.</source>
        </trans-unit>
